<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-458-628  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 458 628.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  July 24 1989 n325 p61(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>With dozens of varieties available, IBM enters 'the biggerpicture.' (special section on PS/2 market)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kinley, Patricia.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM Corp now offers 10 basic PS/2 microcomputer models and nearlythree dozen configurations, ranging from its low-end 8086-basedModels 25 and 30 to the high-end, 386-based Models 60, 70, P70 and80.andP;  It has recently introduced an i486 daughterboard, which canbe plugged into the Model 70 to extend capacity beyond that of theIntel 80386 microprocessor.andP;  Researchers indicate that there is aninstalled base of PS/2s numbering 2 million units.andP;  Though thePS/2 is selling better than the old microcomputer line,MSDOS-based units are still outselling PS/2's by a ratio of nineto one.andP;  This, combined with IBM's introduction of VGA, 3.5-inchfloppy disks, OS/2 and Micro Channel Architecture, precipitated aplunge in IBM's market share to 23 percent in 1988.andP;  IBM hopesthat improved dealer programs, greater variety and an impendingintroduction of 486-based computers will stimulate revenue growth.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     MicrocomputersMarketing StrategyComputer IndustryCompetitionProductsMarket Share.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>